abstract = {Humans spend almost one third of their entire lifetime sleeping. However, Obstructive Sleep Apnea (OSA) is a condition identified as repeated occurrence of partial or complete obstruction of the airway while sleeping, resulting in numerous health complications. Traditional methods for OSA mostly depend on polysomnography (PSG) or manual scoring. But these are intensive in terms of resources and dependent on scorer variability. The study proposes a transformer-based approach for automated OSA event detection utilising electrocardiogram (ECG) data. Here, transformer neural network architecture has been optimized for time-series data, utilizing features extracted from single-lead ECG. Accuracy of 91.97\%, sensitivity of 90.45\%, specificity of 92.92\%, precision of 88.82\%, and F1 score of 0.8962 for PhysioNet Apnea-ECG dataset is achieved by our model. This novel application of deep learning technique could potentially improve the efficiency and accuracy of OSA diagnostics. The rise of AI processing power is currently happening, and our model can be applied to wearable devices for early detection of OSA on any typical individual without using PSG initially.},
